+      <div class="detail-card" data-fid="visual-cta/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">VC-01</span><span class="detail-sev high">HIGH</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Headlines &amp; Buttons</span></div><div class="detail-title">Hero asks for four choices before stating the offer</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">hero-fitment</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The above-fold desktop hero is dominated by a four-step fitment flow on top of a lifestyle image, but there is no visible homepage headline, subhead, or explicit promise about what AWDMods specializes in before shoppers are asked to choose a vehicle.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Add a plain-language H1 and one support line above the selector row so new visitors understand the store&#39;s focus before they invest effort in the fitment flow.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Visitors need a five-second answer to what the store sells and why it is relevant before they will happily complete a multi-step filter.
+â†³ Strong ecommerce heroes explain the offer immediately and pair the main action with essential above-fold context. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Hero Section Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://cxl.com/blog/5-second-test/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="visual-cta/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="visual-cta/F-02"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">VC-02</span><span class="detail-sev high">HIGH</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Headlines &amp; Buttons</span></div><div class="detail-title">Desktop primary action becomes icon-only at the moment of intent</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">hero-cta</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">After configuring Ford &gt; Focus &gt; 2018 &gt; RS, the primary button is enabled but still renders as a 59x59 icon-led control on desktop even though the DOM text remains `Find parts`, which makes the next step look secondary and easy to miss.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Keep the full `Find parts` label visible on desktop and give the button enough width and contrast to read as the dominant next action.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">High-intent shoppers hesitate when the main CTA looks like a utility icon instead of a clear continuation of the flow.
+â†³ Trust and CTA performance improve when the next step is explicit, prominent, and visually unambiguous. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Hero Section Psychology, Trust And Credibility</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://baymard.com/blog/current-state-of-ecommerce-category-ux" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="visual-cta/F-02">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="trust-credibility/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">TC-01</span><span class="detail-sev high">HIGH</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Trust &amp; Credibility</span></div><div class="detail-title">Trust proof is missing beside the fitment decision</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">hero-fitment</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The homepage asks for vehicle details immediately, but there are no review counts, return cues, payment reassurance, or service promises adjacent to the hero flow; the only broad trust signals visible in code are a slim free-shipping strip and footer payment icons far below.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Add a compact trust row directly under the hero with review proof, shipping promise, and a clear return or support reassurance.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Unknown and enthusiast-specialist brands need reassurance closest to the point where shoppers decide whether to continue.
+â†³ Trust signals work best when they sit beside the CTA instead of being buried elsewhere on the page. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Trust And Credibility, Hero Section Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://baymard.com/blog/customers-perceive-only-parts-of-a-checkout-page-as-being-secure" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="trust-credibility/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="trust-credibility/F-02"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">TC-02</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Trust &amp; Credibility</span></div><div class="detail-title">Social proof appears inconsistently across featured products</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">product-rating</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">Some featured cards display rating and review-count modules while adjacent products present no comparable proof, which creates uneven credibility inside the same merch surface.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Standardize review presentation across featured cards or suppress empty review states until proof coverage is consistent.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Mixed proof states make the collection feel less dependable because shoppers cannot tell whether missing reviews mean low demand or missing instrumentation.
+â†³ Even a small review base can materially improve purchase confidence, so inconsistent display leaves money on the table. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Trust And Credibility, Product Cards</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://spiegel.medill.northwestern.edu/how-online-reviews-influence-sales/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="trust-credibility/F-02">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="pricing/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">PR-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Price &amp; Offers</span></div><div class="detail-title">Price is visible but value context is not</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">made-to-order-badge</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">Product cards show prices and some `Made to Order` badges, but there is no nearby explanation of shipping threshold, lead-time implications, or return expectations, so shoppers see cost without the supporting value frame.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Add compact price-adjacent context such as free-shipping threshold, build-time guidance for made-to-order items, and a short returns cue near card pricing.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Price judgments are easier to accept when shoppers can instantly evaluate shipping tradeoffs, wait time, and downside protection.
+â†³ Shipping and return framing materially change conversion because shoppers use them to interpret the real cost of saying yes. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Pricing Psychology, Trust And Credibility</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://www.reddoor.biz/work/case-studies/nuface-finding-the-right-incentive-for-customers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="pricing/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="checkout-flows/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">CF-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Checkout Experience</span></div><div class="detail-title">Checkout convenience cues are buried in the footer</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">payment-icons</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">Apple Pay, Shop Pay, and other payment icons exist in the footer DOM, but the homepage never surfaces comparable convenience messaging near the hero or featured collection, so painless checkout is hidden until the very bottom of the page.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Surface express-checkout and payment reassurance higher in the funnel, ideally near the hero and the first merch module.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Reassuring shoppers that checkout will be fast and familiar reduces uncertainty before they commit to browsing deeper.
+â†³ Early payment reassurance can improve conversion, but only when shoppers see it before they start second-guessing the path. [Silver]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Trust And Credibility</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://stripe.com/blog/testing-the-conversion-impact-of-50-plus-global-payment-methods" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="checkout-flows/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="performance-ux/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">PU-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Performance &amp; UX</span></div><div class="detail-title">Homepage browsing starts after multiple stacked decision layers</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">featured-heading</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">Desktop visitors encounter announcement bar, main nav, large hero image, fitment row, and a five-card category band before the featured collection begins, which delays the first real product comparison surface.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Compress the hero stack or pull a tighter featured product module higher so shoppers can browse sooner without clearing multiple layers first.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">The longer it takes to reach browsable merch, the more likely casual and first-time visitors are to bounce before they see enough inventory depth to continue.
+â†³ Pages convert better when above-fold priority is given to the elements that help visitors act fastest, not just to decorative space. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Hero Section Psychology, Page Performance Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://baymard.com/blog/current-state-of-ecommerce-category-ux" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="performance-ux/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="product-media/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">PM-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Product Photos &amp; Video</span></div><div class="detail-title">Featured cards lean on quick view more than product evidence</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">quick-view-button</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The featured cards use a small quick-view affordance and single-thumbnail presentation, but they do not expose richer fitment proof, alternate context, or stronger evidence on the card itself before asking shoppers to interact.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Use the card surface for stronger evidence first, such as fitment-compatible messaging, richer secondary imagery, or clearer spec/value cues before quick view.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Shoppers compare faster when the collection card itself does more explanatory work and does not require an extra exploratory click to feel credible.
+â†³ Better hierarchy and richer hover or secondary context improve list scanning because users can evaluate items without breaking flow. [Silver]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Image Quantity Types, Product Cards</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://baymard.com/blog/secondary-hover-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="product-media/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="category-navigation/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">CN-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Browse &amp; Search</span></div><div class="detail-title">Category shortcuts do not carry the shopper&#39;s vehicle context</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">category-card</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The homepage offers broad category cards like `Performance` and `Electronics`, but the cards do not restate or preserve the vehicle-selection context that the hero just requested, leaving shoppers to bridge the relevance gap themselves.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Add a persistent `Shop your vehicle by category` path or inject the selected vehicle into category destinations and labels once fitment is known.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Navigation feels easier when the site carries the shopper&#39;s context forward instead of forcing them to keep translating broad categories into their own use case.
+â†³ Visitors increasingly expect relevant paths to reflect their context, and frustration grows when that context is not used. [Silver]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Collection Page Architecture, Personalization Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/specialty/ecommerce/crawling" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="category-navigation/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="content-seo/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">CS-01</span><span class="detail-sev high">HIGH</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Search Findability</span></div><div class="detail-title">Homepage sends weak relevance signals to search and AI systems</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">meta name=&quot;description&quot;</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">Raw HTML uses the generic title `AWDMods - AWDMods`, contains no meta description, and has no H1, so the homepage lacks a crawl-visible statement of category focus or value proposition.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Rewrite the title and meta description around AWD performance parts and install a single H1 that matches the visible homepage promise.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Weak metadata invites title rewrites, lowers click-through leverage, and makes the homepage less legible to both search engines and AI shopping surfaces.
+â†³ Search systems rewrite vague titles frequently, so clear metadata and structure are essential if you want the homepage to carry the right story. [Gold]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Title Formulas SERP Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://zyppy.com/seo/google-title-rewrite-study/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="content-seo/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="post-purchase/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">PP-01</span><span class="detail-sev medium">MEDIUM</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">After Purchase</span></div><div class="detail-title">Retention is delegated to a newsletter block instead of a support promise</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">newsletter-input</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The lower page gives significant space to a newsletter signup, but there is no equally visible post-purchase confidence message about delivery support, review loops, referral momentum, or ownership help; `Track My Order` is only a footer link.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Reframe the lower-page retention block around post-purchase confidence and ownership lifecycle value, then keep email capture as a secondary action.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Shoppers are more willing to buy when the brand signals what happens after checkout, not just how it will collect their email.
+â†³ Post-purchase confidence reduces anxiety and improves repeat behavior, so bottom-of-page retention should reinforce support as well as capture. [Silver]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Post Purchase Psychology, Buyers Remorse</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-narvar-report-finds-two-thirds-of-online-shoppers-feel-anxious-after-they-click-buy-302606853.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="post-purchase/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div><div class="detail-card" data-fid="audience/F-01"><div class="detail-head"><div class="detail-head-row"><span class="detail-id">AU-01</span><span class="detail-sev high">HIGH</span><span class="detail-cluster-tag">Audience Fit</span></div><div class="detail-title">The homepage makes shoppers do the segmentation work themselves</div></div><div class="detail-body"><div class="detail-section"><h4>Element</h4><div class="detail-element">hero-fitment</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Observation</h4><div class="detail-text">The page clearly serves AWD performance owners, but it never says which vehicles, build types, or shopper identities are best served before asking for four fitment choices, so audience recognition exists in the filter logic rather than in the message.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Recommendation</h4><div class="detail-rec">Add a short audience line that names the core vehicle communities and signals whether the store is built for daily drivers, tuners, or high-intent enthusiasts.</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Why this matters</h4><div class="detail-text">Segment-recognition copy lowers interpretation work and helps qualified visitors feel instantly understood instead of merely processed.
+â†³ Shoppers respond better when the experience clearly signals that the store understands their context and priorities. [Silver]</div></div><div class="detail-section"><h4>Source</h4><div class="detail-source"><div class="detail-source-name">Hero Section Psychology, Personalization Psychology</div><div class="detail-source-tier"><a href="https://cxl.com/blog/value-proposition-examples-how-to-create/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open primary source ↗</a></div></div></div></div><div class="detail-actions"><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-skip">Skip</button><button class="detail-btn detail-btn-add" data-fid="audience/F-01">Add to brief</button></div></div>
