n only one full card and part of the next are visible at a time.", "recommendation": "Standardize review coverage on featured cards and keep the most persuasive proof inside the first fully visible card frame.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "pricing/F-01", "cluster": "pricing", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "MEDIUM", "title": "Mobile product cards show price without enough delivery context", "observation": "The carousel cards expose price and `Made to Order` badges, but they do not explain shipping thresholds, wait-time implications, or returns context, so mobile shoppers see cost without enough decision support.", "recommendation": "Add compact mobile card copy for shipping threshold, expected build lead time on made-to-order items, and a short returns cue.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "checkout-flows/F-01", "cluster": "checkout-flows", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "MEDIUM", "title": "Express-checkout reassurance is hidden until the footer", "observation": "Apple Pay, Shop Pay, and other payment methods are present in the footer area, but mobile shoppers do not encounter equivalent convenience messaging near the hero or first merch module.", "recommendation": "Surface express-checkout and payment-trust messaging above the fold or directly above the first product carousel.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "performance-ux/F-01", "cluster": "performance-ux", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "HIGH", "title": "Mobile comparison starts too late and scans too slowly", "observation": "The first real product-comparison surface appears only after a tall hero stack, and then the featured module presents one full card plus a partial next card, which slows scan speed and comparison confidence.", "recommendation": "Reduce the hero stack height and redesign the first merch module so multiple cues or stronger next-card visibility appear earlier in the mobile journey.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "product-media/F-01", "cluster": "product-media", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "MEDIUM", "title": "Quick view and a single image do too much of the card's selling work", "observation": "The mobile card presentation leans on a quick-view control and a single image rather than exposing stronger fitment confidence or richer context directly inside the product card.", "recommendation": "Strengthen the first card view with better evidence on-card, such as clearer fitment relevance, stronger secondary image context, or a more informative product summary.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "category-navigation/F-01", "cluster": "category-navigation", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "MEDIUM", "title": "Category routes appear after the fitment stack instead of accelerating it", "observation": "The mobile category cards do not appear until after the tall fitment flow, so they act as a second discovery layer instead of an early shortcut into relevant merch lanes.", "recommendation": "Bring category shortcuts up sooner or let the fitment flow hand off directly into a `Shop your vehicle by category` experience.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "content-seo/F-01", "cluster": "content-seo", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "HIGH", "title": "Mobile still inherits weak homepage metadata and structure", "observation": "The raw homepage HTML still carries the generic title `AWDMods - AWDMods`, no meta description, and no H1, which means the mobile entry point provides weak relevance signals to search and AI discovery systems.", "recommendation": "Rewrite the homepage title and meta description around AWD performance parts and install a visible H1 aligned to the mobile hero promise.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "post-purchase/F-01", "cluster": "post-purchase", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "MEDIUM", "title": "Lower-page retention still centers email capture over ownership confidence", "observation": "The lower mobile experience emphasizes newsletter signup, but it does not give equal visibility to delivery confidence, support promises, referral momentum, or post-purchase help; `Track My Order` remains buried in footer navigation.", "recommendation": "Recast the lower-page module around post-purchase confidence and ownership lifecycle value, then position email signup as a secondary follow-up action.", "ethics_state": ""}, {"fid": "audience/F-01", "cluster": "audience", "cluster_index": 1, "priority": "HIGH", "title": "Mobile visitors are not told who the store is built for", "observation": "The mobile hero collects detailed vehicle data, but it never proactively names the core AWD platforms, ownership goals, or buyer identities the store serves best before those fields appear.", "recommendation": "Add a short audience-recognition line naming the key vehicle communities and the kind of owner AWDMods is built to help.", "ethics_state": ""}];
+  var EXPORT_MARKDOWN     = [{"fid": "visual-cta/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: FAIL\nTITLE: Mobile hero still lacks a visible promise before the fitment flow\nSECTION: hero-promise-mobile\nELEMENT: hero-fitment\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: The first mobile screen is dominated by the vehicle selector stack, but there is still no visible homepage headline, subhead, or explicit promise clarifying what AWDMods offers before the shopper starts filling fields.\nRECOMMENDATION: Add a concise H1 and support line above the fitment stack so mobile visitors understand the category focus before they invest thumb effort.\nREFERENCE: hero-section-psychology.md Finding 1; hero-section-psychology.md Finding 4\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-hero-throughput\n**Why this matters:** Mobile users decide even faster than desktop users whether the page is relevant, so the promise cannot hide behind a multi-step form.\nâ†³ Ecommerce heroes work best when the value proposition is visible immediately instead of requiring interaction to discover the offer. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "visual-cta/F-02", "block": "```\nFINDING: FAIL\nTITLE: The stacked fitment flow consumes the first decision window\nSECTION: hero-flow-depth\nELEMENT: hero-cta\nSOURCE: VISUAL\nOBSERVATION: Mobile requires four stacked dropdowns plus a CTA before the shopper reaches any meaningful browsing module, which makes the homepage feel like a task flow first and a storefront second.\nRECOMMENDATION: Compress the fitment module, consider progressive disclosure, and allow product/category discovery to appear earlier on the first two screens.\nREFERENCE: hero-section-psychology.md Finding 8; page-performance-psychology.md Finding 9\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-hero-throughput\n**Why this matters:** When the first usable shopping cue is delayed by a tall form stack, casual visitors lose momentum before the site proves its inventory depth.\nâ†³ Above-fold mobile real estate should prioritize immediate comprehension and the fastest route into meaningful browsing. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "trust-credibility/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: FAIL\nTITLE: The mobile CTA has almost no adjacent reassurance\nSECTION: trust-near-mobile-cta\nELEMENT: hero-cta\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: The mobile `FIND PARTS` CTA is easy to read, but it is not paired with review proof, delivery reassurance, return policy cues, or payment confidence directly around the hero stack.\nRECOMMENDATION: Add a mobile trust strip under the CTA with reviews, shipping promise, and a plain-language support or returns cue.\nREFERENCE: trust-and-credibility.md Finding 8; trust-and-credibility.md Finding 18; hero-section-psychology.md Finding 10\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-reassurance-gap\n**Why this matters:** Small screens compress attention, so reassurance has to travel with the primary action instead of living elsewhere on the page.\nâ†³ Trust cues are most persuasive when they sit next to the CTA and reduce perceived risk at the exact decision moment. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "trust-credibility/F-02", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Social proof in the featured carousel feels patchy\nSECTION: mobile-social-proof\nELEMENT: product-rating\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: Review signals appear inconsistently in the mobile featured carousel, and some proof sits partially out of view when only one full card and part of the next are visible at a time.\nRECOMMENDATION: Standardize review coverage on featured cards and keep the most persuasive proof inside the first fully visible card frame.\nREFERENCE: trust-and-credibility.md Finding 3; product-cards.md Finding 1\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-reassurance-gap\n**Why this matters:** Mobile shoppers cannot compare trust signals efficiently when the evidence is inconsistent and partially hidden by the carousel presentation.\nâ†³ Review proof lifts confidence fastest when it is visible on the first comparison surface instead of being intermittent or buried. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "pricing/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Mobile product cards show price without enough delivery context\nSECTION: mobile-price-context\nELEMENT: made-to-order-badge\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: The carousel cards expose price and `Made to Order` badges, but they do not explain shipping thresholds, wait-time implications, or returns context, so mobile shoppers see cost without enough decision support.\nRECOMMENDATION: Add compact mobile card copy for shipping threshold, expected build lead time on made-to-order items, and a short returns cue.\nREFERENCE: pricing-psychology.md Finding 15; pricing-psychology.md Finding 16; trust-and-credibility.md Finding 20\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-reassurance-gap\n**Why this matters:** On mobile there is less room to infer tradeoffs, so missing value context makes prices feel riskier than they need to.\nâ†³ Shipping and return framing often decide whether a displayed price feels fair or incomplete. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "checkout-flows/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Express-checkout reassurance is hidden until the footer\nSECTION: mobile-checkout-assurance\nELEMENT: payment-icons\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: Apple Pay, Shop Pay, and other payment methods are present in the footer area, but mobile shoppers do not encounter equivalent convenience messaging near the hero or first merch module.\nRECOMMENDATION: Surface express-checkout and payment-trust messaging above the fold or directly above the first product carousel.\nREFERENCE: trust-and-credibility.md Finding 14; trust-and-credibility.md Finding 8\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-reassurance-gap\n**Why this matters:** Early checkout reassurance reduces uncertainty on mobile, where friction expectations are already high and patience is low.\nâ†³ Convenience cues perform best when shoppers see them before they commit to a deeper funnel path. [Silver]\n```"}, {"fid": "performance-ux/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Mobile comparison starts too late and scans too slowly\nSECTION: mobile-browse-latency\nELEMENT: featured-grid\nSOURCE: VISUAL\nOBSERVATION: The first real product-comparison surface appears only after a tall hero stack, and then the featured module presents one full card plus a partial next card, which slows scan speed and comparison confidence.\nRECOMMENDATION: Reduce the hero stack height and redesign the first merch module so multiple cues or stronger next-card visibility appear earlier in the mobile journey.\nREFERENCE: hero-section-psychology.md Finding 8; product-cards.md Finding 14\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-comparison-friction\n**Why this matters:** Mobile shoppers need to grasp choice and momentum quickly; long delays and narrow comparison windows make browsing feel heavier than it should.\nâ†³ Faster comparison flows win on mobile because shoppers are far less willing to work through slow discovery patterns. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "product-media/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Quick view and a single image do too much of the card's selling work\nSECTION: mobile-card-evidence\nELEMENT: quick-view-button\nSOURCE: VISUAL\nOBSERVATION: The mobile card presentation leans on a quick-view control and a single image rather than exposing stronger fitment confidence or richer context directly inside the product card.\nRECOMMENDATION: Strengthen the first card view with better evidence on-card, such as clearer fitment relevance, stronger secondary image context, or a more informative product summary.\nREFERENCE: image-quantity-types.md Finding 6; product-cards.md Finding 14\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-comparison-friction\n**Why this matters:** Mobile cards need to carry more explanatory load because every extra tap or modal interrupts the shopper's momentum.\nâ†³ Better hierarchy and richer product-list context help users evaluate items without detouring into extra interactions. [Silver]\n```"}, {"fid": "category-navigation/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Category routes appear after the fitment stack instead of accelerating it\nSECTION: mobile-category-routing\nELEMENT: category-card\nSOURCE: VISUAL\nOBSERVATION: The mobile category cards do not appear until after the tall fitment flow, so they act as a second discovery layer instead of an early shortcut into relevant merch lanes.\nRECOMMENDATION: Bring category shortcuts up sooner or let the fitment flow hand off directly into a `Shop your vehicle by category` experience.\nREFERENCE: collection-page-architecture.md Finding 1; search-and-filter-ux.md Finding 21\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-comparison-friction\n**Why this matters:** Mobile shoppers benefit when routing choices accelerate discovery instead of waiting behind the page's heaviest interaction block.\nâ†³ Filters and navigation perform better when they are promoted at the moment users are deciding how to browse, not after they have already worked through friction. [Silver]\n```"}, {"fid": "content-seo/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: FAIL\nTITLE: Mobile still inherits weak homepage metadata and structure\nSECTION: head-metadata-mobile\nELEMENT: meta name=\"description\"\nSOURCE: DOM\nOBSERVATION: The raw homepage HTML still carries the generic title `AWDMods - AWDMods`, no meta description, and no H1, which means the mobile entry point provides weak relevance signals to search and AI discovery systems.\nRECOMMENDATION: Rewrite the homepage title and meta description around AWD performance parts and install a visible H1 aligned to the mobile hero promise.\nREFERENCE: title-formulas-serp-psychology.md Finding 3; title-formulas-serp-psychology.md Finding 5\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-discoverability-gap\n**Why this matters:** Better metadata improves the quality of the click before mobile visitors ever land, and it keeps the homepage message consistent across acquisition channels.\nâ†³ Generic titles are frequently rewritten, so a clearer structured promise is critical for discoverability. [Gold]\n```"}, {"fid": "post-purchase/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: PARTIAL\nTITLE: Lower-page retention still centers email capture over ownership confidence\nSECTION: mobile-lifecycle-retention\nELEMENT: newsletter-input\nSOURCE: VISUAL+DOM\nOBSERVATION: The lower mobile experience emphasizes newsletter signup, but it does not give equal visibility to delivery confidence, support promises, referral momentum, or post-purchase help; `Track My Order` remains buried in footer navigation.\nRECOMMENDATION: Recast the lower-page module around post-purchase confidence and ownership lifecycle value, then position email signup as a secondary follow-up action.\nREFERENCE: post-purchase-psychology.md Finding 1; post-purchase-psychology.md Finding 6; buyers-remorse.md Finding 7\nPRIORITY: MEDIUM\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-discoverability-gap\n**Why this matters:** Buyers feel better about purchasing when they can picture the support and follow-up they will receive after conversion, not just the email list they will join.\nâ†³ Post-purchase assurance lowers anxiety and strengthens repeat intent, making it more persuasive than capture-first messaging alone. [Silver]\n```"}, {"fid": "audience/F-01", "block": "```\nFINDING: FAIL\nTITLE: Mobile visitors are not told who the store is built for\nSECTION: mobile-audience-recognition\nELEMENT: hero-fitment\nSOURCE: VISUAL\nOBSERVATION: The mobile hero collects detailed vehicle data, but it never proactively names the core AWD platforms, ownership goals, or buyer identities the store serves best before those fields appear.\nRECOMMENDATION: Add a short audience-recognition line naming the key vehicle communities and the kind of owner AWDMods is built to help.\nREFERENCE: hero-section-psychology.md Finding 2; personalization-psychology.md Finding 11\nPRIORITY: HIGH\nSYNTHESIS_HINT: mobile-hero-throughput\n**Why this matters:** When the store recognizes the shopper's context first, the fitment flow feels like guidance instead of like unpaid classification work.\nâ†³ Experience quality rises when visitors feel the site understands them before asking them to supply more data. [Silver]\n```"}];
